old.text:
In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires,—
(1) 'advance tax' means the advance tax payable in accordance with the provisions of Chapter XVII-C;
(7) 'assessee' means a person by whom any tax or any other sum of money is payable under this Act;
(8) 'assessment' includes reassessment;
(9) 'assessment year' means the period of twelve months commencing on the 1st day of April every year;
(24) 'income' includes—(i) profits and gains; (ii) dividend; (iii) voluntary contributions received by a trust...
(31) 'person' includes—(i) an individual; (ii) a Hindu undivided family; (iii) a company; (iv) a firm; (v) an association of persons or a body of individuals...
(42A) 'short-term capital asset' means a capital asset held for not more than thirty-six months immediately preceding the date of its transfer;
(42B) 'long-term capital asset' means a capital asset which is not a short-term capital asset.

new.text:
In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires,—
(1) 'advance tax' means advance tax payable under Chapter XVII;
(4) 'assessee' means a person by whom tax or any other sum is payable under this Act, and includes a person in respect of whom any proceeding has been taken;
(5) 'assessment' includes reassessment and best judgment assessment;
(6) 'assessment year'— the concept of 'assessment year' is replaced by 'tax year' under section 3;
(21) 'income' has the same inclusive meaning as under the 1961 Act, now defined with greater clarity in sub-clauses;
(38) 'person' includes individual, HUF, company, firm, AOP, BOI, local authority and every artificial juridical person;
'short-term capital asset' and 'long-term capital asset' — definitions now aligned with revised holding periods specified in Chapter IV.

Save as otherwise provided by this Act, all income shall, for the purposes of charge of income-tax and computation of total income, be classified under the following heads:—
(a) Salaries;
(b) Income from house property;
(c) Profits and gains of business or profession;
(d) Capital gains;
(e) Income from other sources.

Note: The head 'Interest on securities' (Head B under 1961 Act) has been merged into 'Income from other sources'.

old.text:
The following income shall be chargeable to income-tax under the head 'Salaries':—
(a) any salary due from an employer or a former employer to an assessee in the previous year, whether paid or not;
(b) any salary paid or allowed to him in the previous year by or on behalf of an employer or a former employer though not due or before it became due to him;
(c) any arrears of salary paid or allowed to him in the previous year by or on behalf of an employer or a former employer, if not charged to income-tax for any earlier previous year.

new.text:
The following income shall be chargeable under the head 'Salaries':—
(a) salary due from an employer or former employer, whether paid or not;
(b) salary paid or allowed in the tax year before it became due;
(c) arrears of salary paid in the tax year not charged to tax in any earlier tax year.

Explanation.— Where salary is due from an employer, it shall be chargeable in the tax year in which it is due, irrespective of the tax year to which it relates.

In computing income under the head 'Salaries', the following deductions shall be allowed:—
(1) Standard deduction: ₹75,000 or the amount of salary, whichever is less. [Increased from ₹50,000]
(2) Entertainment allowance: deduction in respect of entertainment allowance specifically granted by the employer, subject to limits for government employees.
(3) Professional tax: deduction of the amount of any tax on employment paid during the tax year.
(4) Retirement and separation receipts [Consolidated from §10(10), §10(10A), §10(10AA), §10(10B), §10(10C)]:—
  (a) Gratuity received on retirement/death — exempt up to specified limits;
  (b) Commuted pension — exempt as prescribed;
  (c) Leave encashment on retirement — exempt up to ₹25 lakh;
  (d) Retrenchment compensation — exempt up to prescribed limits;
  (e) VRS compensation — exempt up to ₹5 lakh.

old.text:
The following income shall be chargeable to income-tax under the head 'Profits and gains of business or profession':—
(i) the profits and gains of any business or profession which was carried on by the assessee at any time during the previous year;
(ii) any compensation or other payment due to or received by,—
(a) any person, by whatever name called, managing the whole or substantially the whole of the affairs of an Indian company, at or in connection with the termination of his management or the modification of the terms and conditions relating thereto;
(iii) income derived by a trade, professional or similar association from specific services performed for its members;
(iv) the value of any benefit or perquisite, whether convertible into money or not, arising from business or the exercise of a profession;
(vi) any interest, salary, bonus, commission or remuneration due to or received by a partner from the firm.

new.text:
The following income shall be chargeable under the head 'Profits and gains of business or profession':—
(a) profits and gains of any business or profession carried on by the assessee at any time during the tax year;
(b) any compensation received in connection with termination or modification of a management contract;
(c) income derived by a trade or professional association from specific services to its members;
(d) the value of any benefit or perquisite, whether convertible into money or not, arising from business or profession;
(e) any interest, salary, bonus, commission or remuneration received by a partner from the firm in which they are a partner;
(f) any sum received under a Keyman insurance policy including bonus.

