new.text:
(1) The following deductions shall be allowed:—
(a) insurance premium against risk of damage or destruction of stocks;
(b) bonus or commission to employees;
(c) employer's contribution to recognised provident fund or approved superannuation fund;
(d) employer's contribution to approved gratuity fund;
(e) bad debts written off as irrecoverable in the accounts of the tax year (subject to the conditions in sub-section (2));
(f) contributions to Rural Infrastructure Development Fund or fund set up by NHB.

Section 30 — Premium deductions (insurance premiums for all assets)
Section 31 — Bad debts and provisions for doubtful debts (banks)
Section 32 — Miscellaneous specific deductions

Notwithstanding anything in any other provision, a deduction otherwise allowable shall be allowed only in the tax year in which the following sums are actually paid:—
(a) any tax, duty, cess or fee payable under any law;
(b) employer's contribution to provident fund, superannuation fund, gratuity fund or any other employee welfare fund;
(c) bonus or commission to employees;
(d) interest on loans from public financial institutions, State financial corporations or scheduled banks or co-operative banks;
(e) leave encashment in lieu of leave at the credit of the employee;
(f) payment to Indian Railways for use of railway assets;
(g) payment to MSME suppliers — allowed only on actual payment within the time limit specified under the MSMED Act, 2006. [New clause added]

old.text:
Every person,—
(a) carrying on business shall, if his total sales, turnover or gross receipts, as the case may be, in business exceed or exceeds one crore rupees in any previous year;
(b) carrying on profession shall, if his gross receipts in profession exceed fifty lakh rupees in any previous year;
(c) carrying on business and who has declared profits and gains for the previous year in accordance with the provisions of section 44AD;
(d) carrying on business and who has not declared profits or gains for the previous year in accordance with the provisions of section 44ADA;
get his accounts of such previous year audited by an accountant before the specified date and furnish by that date the report of such audit in the prescribed form duly signed and verified by such accountant.

new.text:
Every person—
(a) carrying on business, if total sales, turnover or gross receipts exceed ₹1 crore in any tax year [₹10 crore if cash receipts and payments do not exceed 5% of total receipts and payments];
(b) carrying on profession, if gross receipts exceed ₹50 lakh;
(c) opting out of presumptive taxation under §58 (business) or §59 (profession) after having opted in;
must get accounts audited by a Chartered Accountant and furnish the audit report in the prescribed form before the due date.

Explanation.— The threshold of ₹1 crore is enhanced to ₹10 crore for digital businesses (cash transactions ≤ 5%).

old.text:
(1) Income of every kind which is not to be excluded from the total income under this Act shall be chargeable to income-tax under the head 'Income from other sources', if it is not chargeable to income-tax under any of the heads specified in section 14, items A to E.
(2) In particular, and without prejudice to the generality of the provisions of sub-section (1), the following income shall be chargeable to income-tax under the head 'Income from other sources', namely:—
(i) dividends;
(ii) income from winnings from lotteries, crossword puzzles, races including horse races, card games and other games of any sort or from gambling or betting of any form or nature;
(viia) where any immovable property is received without consideration, the stamp duty value of such property, if the stamp duty value of such property exceeds fifty thousand rupees;
(x) where any person receives, in any previous year, from any person or persons on or after the 1st day of April, 2017,—
(a) any sum of money, without consideration, the aggregate value of which exceeds fifty thousand rupees, the whole of the aggregate value;
(b) any immovable property,—
(i) without consideration, the stamp duty value of which exceeds fifty thousand rupees, the stamp duty value;
(ii) for a consideration, the stamp duty value exceeds such consideration by more than the higher of the following amounts, namely:— fifty thousand rupees; five per cent of the consideration.

new.text:
(1) Income not chargeable under any other head shall be chargeable under 'Income from other sources'.
(2) The following shall, in particular, be chargeable under this head:—
(a) dividends;
(b) winnings from lotteries, crossword puzzles, races, card games, gambling or betting;
(c) interest on securities;
(d) gifts received [gifts-in-kind threshold]:—
  (i) sum of money received without consideration exceeding ₹50,000 — whole amount taxable;
  (ii) immovable property received without consideration — stamp duty value taxable if exceeding ₹50,000;
  (iii) immovable property received for inadequate consideration — difference between stamp duty value and consideration taxable if gap > ₹50,000 or 10% of consideration [threshold increased from 5% to 10%];
  (iv) movable property received without consideration — fair market value taxable if exceeding ₹50,000.
(e) income from virtual digital assets (VDAs/crypto) not covered under capital gains.

old.text:
(1) In computing the total income of an assessee, being an individual or a Hindu undivided family, there shall be deducted, in accordance with and subject to the provisions of this section, the whole of the amount paid or deposited in the previous year, being the aggregate of the sums referred to in sub-section (2), as does not exceed one lakh and fifty thousand rupees.
(2) The sums referred to in sub-section (1) shall be any sums paid or deposited in the previous year by the assessee—
(i) as premium to effect or to keep in force an insurance on the life of the assessee, the spouse or any child of the assessee;
(ii) as a contribution by the assessee to any provident fund to which the Provident Funds Act, 1925 applies;
(iii) as subscription to any notified savings certificate;
(iv) as contribution by the assessee to a notified Public Provident Fund;
(v) as contribution by the assessee to a notified pension fund;
(xvi) as subscription to any units of any Mutual Fund referred to in clause (23D) of section 10 or from the Unit Trust of India;
(xvii) as a term deposit for a fixed period of not less than five years with a scheduled bank;
(xviii) as subscription to notified bonds issued by the National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development;
(xix) as tuition fees (excluding any payment towards any development fees or donation or payment of similar nature), paid at the time of admission or thereafter to any university, college, school or other educational institution situated within India.

new.text:
(1) An individual or HUF may claim a deduction up to ₹1,50,000 in a tax year for the aggregate of the following:—
(a) life insurance premium for self, spouse or child;
(b) contribution to Provident Fund (GPF, EPF, PPF);
(c) subscription to NSC, NSS or notified savings certificates;
(d) contribution to notified pension fund or Tier-I NPS account;
(e) subscription to ELSS units of a mutual fund;
(f) fixed deposit with scheduled bank for 5 years or more (tax-saver FD);
(g) tuition fees for full-time education of up to two children in India;
(h) repayment of principal on home loan for a residential house;
(i) contribution to Sukanya Samriddhi Yojana.
(2) Contribution to pension fund of LIC or an approved insurer [formerly §80CCC] shall also be included within the ₹1,50,000 limit.
(3) Employee's own NPS contribution [formerly §80CCD(1)] shall be within the ₹1,50,000 limit.
(4) Employer's NPS contribution [formerly §80CCD(2)]: deduction up to 14% of salary [increased from 10%] for central government employees and 10% for others — available even under the new tax regime (§202).

Important: Deductions under sub-sections (1), (2) and (3) are NOT available under the new tax regime (§202). Only sub-section (4) [employer NPS] is available under the new regime.

old.text:
(1) In computing the total income of an assessee, being an individual or a Hindu undivided family, there shall be deducted such sum, as specified in sub-section (2) or sub-section (3), in respect of payments made by the assessee—
(a) towards premium paid for health insurance of self and family: up to ₹25,000;
(b) premium paid for health insurance of parents: additional ₹25,000;
(c) if the insured (self/family/parents) is a senior citizen: ₹50,000;
(d) preventive health check-up: ₹5,000 within the overall limit.
Where the assessee is a HUF: up to ₹25,000 for members.

new.text:
(1) An individual or HUF shall be allowed a deduction for premium paid for health insurance under an approved scheme of GIC or IRDAI-approved insurer:—
(a) for self, spouse and dependent children: up to ₹25,000;
(b) for parents: additional ₹25,000;
(c) where the insured person is a senior citizen: limit enhanced to ₹50,000 per category;
(d) preventive health check-up: ₹5,000 within the above limits.
(2) Payment must be by any mode other than cash (except for preventive check-up).
(3) This deduction is NOT available under the new tax regime (§202).
(4) [New] Deduction also allowed for contribution to Central Government Health Scheme (CGHS) within the same limits.

(1) Where the Assessing Officer has information (as defined) suggesting that income chargeable to tax has escaped assessment, he may reassess or assess such income after following the procedure under §§275–276.
(2) 'Information' means:—
  (a) information from prescribed authorities (SFT, AIS, Form 26AS, etc.);
  (b) information received under DTAA or tax treaties;
  (c) information from audit objections;
  (d) information from court orders.
(3) Time limits for reassessment:—
  — General: within 3 years from the end of the tax year;
  — Where income escaped exceeds ₹50 lakh: within 10 years from the end of the tax year;
  — Search cases: up to 6 years from the end of the tax year.
(4) Reassessment cannot be initiated merely on the basis of a change of opinion. An AO who completes the assessment cannot reassess on grounds that were already considered.

(1) Where an assessee has under-reported income, penalty shall be levied by the Assessing Officer or Appellate Authority at:—
(a) 50% of tax on under-reported income (for under-reporting); or
(b) 200% of tax on misreported income (for misreporting — false entries, suppression, use of forged documents).
(2) Under-reporting means the income assessed exceeds the income declared.
(3) Misreporting includes:—
  (a) misrepresentation or suppression of facts;
  (b) failure to record investments in books;
  (c) claim of expenditure not substantiated;
  (d) recording false entries.
(4) No penalty for under-reporting where:—
  (a) the assessee offers a bona fide explanation;
  (b) the assessee discloses the income in the updated return (ITR-U) filed before issuing the notice.
(5) [New] Immunity from penalty on payment of tax and interest on undisclosed income detected during search, if disclosed in the updated return within the prescribed period.

old.text:
(1) If a person wilfully attempts in any manner whatsoever to evade any tax, penalty or interest chargeable or imposable, or the payment thereof, under this Act, he shall, without prejudice to any penalty that may be imposable on him under any other provision of this Act, be punishable,—
(i) in a case where the amount sought to be evaded exceeds twenty-five lakh rupees, with rigorous imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than six months but which may extend to seven years and with fine;
(ii) in any other case, with rigorous imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than three months but which may extend to two years and with fine.

new.text:
(1) The Central Government may enter into agreements (DTAAs) with foreign governments or specified territories for:—
(a) relief from double taxation on income taxed in both India and the treaty country;
(b) avoidance of double taxation;
(c) exchange of information for prevention of tax evasion;
(d) recovery of taxes.
(2) Where a DTAA applies, the provisions of this Act shall apply to the extent more beneficial to the assessee.
(3) [Codified] A non-resident shall be entitled to the benefit of the DTAA only if they furnish a Tax Residency Certificate (TRC) from the foreign tax authority.
(4) [Codified] The assessee shall also furnish such additional information in Form 10F as prescribed.
(5) The Principal Purpose Test (PPT) applies: DTAA benefits shall not be available where the main purpose of an arrangement is to obtain DTAA benefits — consistent with OECD/BEPS Action 6.
